    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.8.0-dev-1152-g14610332b \n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux Mint 20.2\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKitty 0.15\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nappimage\n\n### How to reproduce the issue\n\n1. `nvim --clean repro.lua`\r\n2. Paste the following Lua code:\r\n```lua\r\nlocal a = \"a\\n\"\r\nlocal b = \"b\\n\"\r\n\r\nvim.diff(a, b, {\r\n  on_hunk = function(_, _, _, _)\r\n    return -1\r\n  end,\r\n  result_type = \"indices\",\r\n})\r\n```\r\n3. `:so %`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo error as I'm just trying to skip a hunk. This is what it says in the docs:\r\n```\r\nâ€¢ `on_hunk` (callback):\r\n  Invoked for each hunk in the diff. Return a\r\n  negative number to cancel the callback for any\r\n  remaining hunks.\r\n```\n\n### Actual behavior\n\n```\r\nError detected while processing /home/user/test.lua:                                                                                                                                                                                   \r\nE5113: Error while calling lua chunk: /home/user/test.lua:4: Error while performing diff operation                                                                                                                                     \r\nstack traceback:                                                                                                                                                                                                                        \r\n        [C]: in function 'diff'                                                                                                                                                                                                         \r\n        /home/user/test.lua:4: in main chunk \r\n```",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I'm not sure there is a way we can return negative from `on_hunk` and *not* error. We may need to change the documentation to say:\r\n\r\n```\r\n Return a negative number to cancel the callback for any remaining hunks and raise an error.\r\n```",
